<span class="displaytext"><b>to: interested parties<br/> from: howard wolfson, communications director<br/> re: south carolina, florida, and february 5<br/> date: january 26, 2008</b> <p>the (candidate last) campaign has been so confident of winning south carolina that six months ago they flatly predicted victory in the palmetto state. </p><p>cornell belcher, senator (candidate last)'s pollster, stated explicitly to the politico on july 25, 2007, "we are going to outright win south carolina." </p><p>and today, senator (candidate last) leads by 12, according to the real clear politics average of polls taken in south carolina over the last 10 days. </p><p>despite senator (candidate last)'s large lead, senator (candidate last) has campaigned across the palmetto state, reaching out and asking for each and every vote. she has heard directly from south carolinians about their concerns and their hopes for a stronger, more prosperous america. </p><p>regardless of today's outcome, the race quickly shifts to florida, where hundreds of thousands of (PARTY NAME) will turn out to vote on tuesday. </p><p>despite efforts by the (candidate last) campaign to ignore floridians, their voices will be heard loud and clear across the country, as the last state to vote before super tuesday on february 5th. </p><p>this remains a delegate fight, with 1,681 delegates at stake on february 5th, and 2,025 needed to secure the nomination -- and we are ahead in that fight. </p><p>as senator (candidate last) has said from the beginning, we have built a national campaign with the resources to compete and win across the country. </p><p>coming off of victories in nevada, michigan and new hampshire, senator (candidate last) has demonstrated the importance of focusing on achieving real solutions on the economy, health care and iraq. </p><p>as she campaigns throughout the united states over the coming weeks, senator (candidate last) will continue to work hard for every vote, making sure that americans know she will be a president who focuses on what matters most--making a difference in people's lives.</p></span>



